@node Bugs and limits
@chapter Bugs and limits

@cindex bugs
@cindex limitations
@cindex known issues

This chapter documents known issues and limitations.  Some are inherited
from the original 1993 codebase; others are architectural limitations
that would require significant rewriting to fix.

@section Fixed in 1.6.x

These bugs existed for years and are now resolved:

@table @strong
@item UTF-8 display garbled (Debian #1137613)
Fixed in v1.6.0.  The 1993 byte-based screen buffer stored each byte of
a UTF-8 sequence as a separate cell, causing border misalignment and
garbled display.  The @code{SCREENCELL} buffer model decodes UTF-8 via
@code{mbrtowc()} and stores one character per cell.

@item Terminal resize not detected (Debian #1137649)
Fixed in v1.6.0.  xwpe now handles @code{KEY_RESIZE} from ncurses to
detect terminal size changes, reallocate buffers, and repaint.

@item Color dialog crash (Debian #228820)
Fixed in v1.5.31.  Dragging the mouse outside the colour table in
@samp{Options @result{} Adjust Colors} caused a segfault due to an
unclamped array index.

@item FTBFS with GCC 15 (Debian #1098180)
Fixed in v1.5.31 (via @code{-std=gnu17}) and permanently in v1.6.1
(automake sets @code{-std=gnu17} automatically).  GCC 15 defaults to
C23 where @code{f()} means @code{f(void)}, breaking K&R-style
declarations.

@item Terminal not reset on exit
Fixed in v1.5.31.  The terminal state is now properly saved and restored
on clean exit.
@end table

@section Known open issues

@table @strong
@item X11 mode does not display UTF-8
The X11 binaries (@command{xwpe}, @command{xwe}) use
@code{XDrawImageString} which does not support multi-byte characters.
UTF-8 text appears garbled or truncated in X11 mode.  Terminal mode
(@command{wpe}, @command{we}) works correctly.

@item Resize does not scale editor proportionally
When the terminal is resized larger in programming mode, the editor
window keeps its original size instead of expanding to fill the available
space.  The @code{KEY_RESIZE} handler expands windows at terminal edges
but does not recalculate the 2/3 ratio for the initial editor window.

@item Debugging leaks memory
The exact source of the leak is unknown.  It has been present since at
least the Payne era (documented in the 1.5.x CHANGELOG).

@item Compilers assumed to have @code{-c} and @code{-o} options
This causes problems for languages whose compilers do not use these
flags (e.g.@: @command{javac}, @command{perl}).  Workaround: use a
wrapper script that translates @code{-c} and @code{-o} into the correct
flags for the target compiler.

@item @command{make install} installs X11 binaries unconditionally
Even when compiled @option{--without-x}, the install target creates
the @command{xwpe} and @command{xwe} symlinks.  These will work (they
just run in terminal mode) but their presence is misleading.

@item Esc key requires 3 presses on Linux console
On the Linux console (and some other terminal types), the @key{ESC} key
must be pressed three times to trigger the escape function.  This is
because xwpe uses @key{ESC} as the prefix for Alt-key sequences, and
the terminal sends the same byte for both.

@item No error on disk full
xwpe does not detect or report write failures due to a full disk.

@item Maximum column and cut/paste interaction
Changing the maximum column setting and then using cut and paste can
crash xwpe.

@item Check Headers does not handle all cases
The ``Check Headers'' feature for C projects does not correctly handle
comments or @code{#ifndef} include guards.

@item Documentation not updated (historical)
The in-app help file (@file{help.xwpe_eng}) has not been updated since
the Payne era (2006).  This Texinfo manual is the current primary
documentation.
@end table

@section Reporting bugs

Report bugs at @uref{https://codeberg.org/mendezr/xwpe/issues}.

For Debian-specific bugs, use @command{reportbug xwpe} or file at
@uref{https://bugs.debian.org/xwpe}.
